comment_message_cleaned: I'm curious to know Stumph, where did you study soil science? »"the amount of each determines the general polarity of the soil"« I will admit that I was slightly wrong when I said earlier that soil has a negative charge. What I meant, and should have stated it better, is that the clay particles in the soil have a negative charge. The soil, as whole, (which would include both the clay particles in the soil and the minerals bound by the clay) actually has no electric charge. The negative charge of the clay particles is offset by the positive charge of the minerals. So, the soil actually has no polarity. Since "soil" actually includes the minerals that are in the dirt.

comment_message_cleaned: I don't necessarily agree with this article. I think the majority of farmers feed and care for their animals properly. Especially dairy farmers as if they want them to keep producing quality milk, they'd be foolish not to. But I disagree that humans play absolutely no part in climate change or environmental damage. Effluent from chemical fertilizers and manure on large farms can pollute nearby rivers and lakes, and one only has to look at smoke spewing from industrial stacks to reason that it must have some effect in the atmosphere. comment_message_cleaned: If we are looking at cattle and habitat destruction vs cars, then, yes, cattle and other livestock may contribute more greenhouse gasses. But the error in the calculation that livestock are worse is that for vehicles, in fairness, habitat destruction and support industry must also be factored. For example, few people stop to think of the millions of acres chewed up to make roads, highways and parking areas. There are whole fields of engineering and city planning devoted to just this, and the sum of destroyed land is vast. The automotive manufacturing and maintenance industries which must mine and manufacture adds to the devastation. The fossil fuel industry, as well as other complex chemical industries for paints, lubricants, etc., adds also to the devastation. Either way it's very bad, though livestock have one saving grace. When raised under more natural conditions, such as the natural grazing conditions of pre-industrial farming, they go a long way toward establishing balance in meadow environments. However, given the massive human overpopulation of the planet, and the ensuing need to cultivate and farm nearly every available scrap of ground in a race against erosion, even that potential benefit is negated.

comment_message_cleaned: ''This spring I was privileged to visit the Africa Centre for Holistic Management (ACHM) in Zimbabwe, and spend several days with Allan Savory, the pioneer and guru of holistic management and managed grazing. Savory is a research biologist who has faced his share of controversy over the years. And you start to get an idea of why this is so, when you hear him utter the phrase: “Only livestock can save us.” A more radical statement could hardly be uttered in this day and age. The media—from newscasts to environmental activists—all seem to agree on this one point: animals are the cause of global warming and we need fewer animals on the planet, not more, if we are to reverse desertification and restore the earth’s grasslands. Allan unabashedly holds and eresses his radically different opinion, at every turn. I was able to talk with him and see the results of his ideas applied practically at the ACHM last May. At this learning hub in Victoria Falls, the Savory Institute staff and volunteers manage the land in a way that is sustainable and regenerative. And livestock are the tool that is turning everything around.'
